1
00:01:38,166 --> 00:01:39,250
[MAGE]
Yuri...

2
00:01:39,333 --> 00:01:42,708
♪

3
00:01:42,791 --> 00:01:45,083
I'm sorry for running
off on my own.

4
00:01:47,166 --> 00:01:49,041
But...

5
00:01:49,125 --> 00:01:51,333
I know that we'll meet again.

6
00:01:51,416 --> 00:01:53,000
Thanks for everything.

7
00:01:53,083 --> 00:01:54,833
I love you.

8
00:01:56,083 --> 00:01:57,833
-[DERRIDA] Mage...
-[click]

9
00:01:59,125 --> 00:02:00,833
She disappeared one day.

10
00:02:00,916 --> 00:02:02,708
This is all she left me.

11
00:02:02,791 --> 00:02:04,416
[VIDAUX]
If the reason they're after her

12
00:02:04,500 --> 00:02:07,500
is because of the access key
to the patch file you gave her,

13
00:02:07,583 --> 00:02:09,208
[footsteps]

14
00:02:09,291 --> 00:02:12,083
why don't you just make another
one and sell it off already?

15
00:02:12,166 --> 00:02:13,708
It's not that simple.

16
00:02:13,791 --> 00:02:15,625
I'd need equipment,

17
00:02:15,708 --> 00:02:17,666
not to mention the time!

18
00:02:17,750 --> 00:02:20,875
So, it seems, you were lying
when you said that brain

19
00:02:20,958 --> 00:02:22,416
of yours
would be worth something to me.

20
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:24,875
I know there are people
who'd want the key!

21
00:02:26,500 --> 00:02:28,000
Wait, hang on a second.

22
00:02:28,958 --> 00:02:31,208
What ever happened to Rebuild?

23
00:02:31,291 --> 00:02:33,500
They haven't been blamed
for all this destruction?

24
00:02:33,583 --> 00:02:35,750
[VIDAUX] [sigh]
Exactly the opposite.

25
00:02:35,833 --> 00:02:38,708
The government brought them
in to stop the rampaging DZs,

26
00:02:38,791 --> 00:02:40,041
and now they're positioned as

27
00:02:40,125 --> 00:02:42,541
the country's largest
defense contractor.

28
00:02:42,625 --> 00:02:44,000
[DERRIDA]
No...

29
00:02:44,083 --> 00:02:46,375
[VIDAUX] Pursuing a case
against Rebuild would make

30
00:02:46,458 --> 00:02:49,041
the government liable as well,
since they're the ones

31
00:02:49,125 --> 00:02:51,166
that commissioned them
in the first place.

32
00:02:51,250 --> 00:02:53,208
Of course they can't
swallow that pill,

33
00:02:53,291 --> 00:02:56,958
so they've let the issue
languish while the war drags on.

34
00:02:57,041 --> 00:02:58,375
-Damn it.
-Hey!

35
00:02:58,458 --> 00:02:59,625
Speaking of Rebuild!

36
00:02:59,708 --> 00:03:02,333
If we accept that
Derrida's story is true,

37
00:03:02,416 --> 00:03:04,458
then the people most
interested in the patch file,

38
00:03:04,541 --> 00:03:07,041
would be Rebuild
and the government.

39
00:03:07,125 --> 00:03:08,583
Yeah, that's right.

40
00:03:08,666 --> 00:03:10,083
Then it stands to reason

41
00:03:10,166 --> 00:03:12,583
that Rebuild has some leads
on where to find Mage!

42
00:03:12,666 --> 00:03:14,125
[gasp]

43
00:03:14,208 --> 00:03:15,750
♪

44
00:03:15,833 --> 00:03:18,250
[DERRIDA] We can't use
the internet? You're kidding.

45
00:03:18,333 --> 00:03:19,833
[VIDAUX]
Don't know what to tell you,

46
00:03:19,916 --> 00:03:21,916
the war's trashed
our infrastructure.

47
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,916
Hardly anywhere except the
city center has a connection.

48
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:26,916
[DERRIDA sighs]

49
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:29,125
[DERRIDA] So, our only option
is infiltrating Rebuild

50
00:03:29,208 --> 00:03:31,208
and using their terminals
to steal the data

51
00:03:31,291 --> 00:03:32,958
from the network directly.

52
00:03:33,041 --> 00:03:34,875
[VIDAUX] There's one
problem with that, too.

53
00:03:34,958 --> 00:03:38,416
[DERRIDA]
Of course there is. What is it?

54
00:03:38,500 --> 00:03:41,208
[VIDAUX] Das Band.
A wall meant to keep refugees

55
00:03:41,291 --> 00:03:42,791
from the city's
war-torn outskirts

56
00:03:42,875 --> 00:03:44,708
from pouring into
the inner limits.

57
00:03:46,250 --> 00:03:49,708
[DERRIDA] All this happened in
the 10 years I've been asleep.

58
00:03:49,791 --> 00:03:50,750
What should we do?

59
00:03:50,833 --> 00:03:52,708
Is there any way to get inside?

60
00:03:55,041 --> 00:03:56,416
[footsteps]

61
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:01,041
[DERRIDA]
Seems so obvious.

62
00:04:01,125 --> 00:04:02,583
Is it safe?

63
00:04:02,666 --> 00:04:05,125
[VIDAUX] There are some nasty
rumors about this place.

64
00:04:05,208 --> 00:04:06,416
[BOTH grimace]

65
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:08,125
[DERRIDA]
Care to elaborate?

66
00:04:09,583 --> 00:04:11,625
[rubble crunching]

67
00:04:19,083 --> 00:04:21,125
♪

68
00:04:25,833 --> 00:04:26,916
[grunt]

69
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:28,333
[sigh]

70
00:04:28,416 --> 00:04:29,750
[groan]

71
00:04:31,750 --> 00:04:33,166
-[squeak]
-[BOTH gasp]

72
00:04:35,041 --> 00:04:36,208
[DERRIDA]
Hey.

73
00:04:36,291 --> 00:04:38,041
You still haven't
answered my question.

74
00:04:38,125 --> 00:04:39,458
I dunno.

75
00:04:39,541 --> 00:04:41,375
Might've been a gas leak
or a cave-in,

76
00:04:41,458 --> 00:04:44,500
but people keep dying in here
and repairs end up stalling.

77
00:04:44,583 --> 00:04:45,500
So...

78
00:04:45,583 --> 00:04:47,500
Oh no. It's not...

79
00:04:47,583 --> 00:04:49,625
a ghost, is it?

80
00:04:49,708 --> 00:04:51,333
[VIDAUX] I wish it was
something that whimsical.

81
00:04:51,416 --> 00:04:53,458
Tell ya what, though,
since I'm feeling generous,

82
00:04:53,541 --> 00:04:55,041
I won't charge extra for this.

83
00:04:55,125 --> 00:04:56,916
[DERRIDA] Are you really
talking about my tab right now?

84
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:58,083
[VIDAUX]
I told you.

85
00:04:58,166 --> 00:05:00,083
I don't work for free.

86
00:05:00,166 --> 00:05:02,166
[YURI] Come on!
So if someone's in trouble,

87
00:05:02,250 --> 00:05:04,708
but they don't have any money,
you'd abandon them?

88
00:05:04,791 --> 00:05:06,166
[VIDAUX]
Yeah.

89
00:05:06,250 --> 00:05:09,083
It's not my job to
be a bleeding heart.

90
00:05:09,166 --> 00:05:10,958
Doesn't your conscience
ever bother you?

91
00:05:11,041 --> 00:05:12,125
Conscience?

92
00:05:12,208 --> 00:05:13,916
I don't trust
something like that.

93
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,541
Wow, seriously?

94
00:05:17,625 --> 00:05:19,166
[DERRIDA sighs]

95
00:05:19,250 --> 00:05:21,625
-I'll make money, or rather...
-Huh?

96
00:05:22,583 --> 00:05:24,083
There's a man named Andrei.

97
00:05:24,166 --> 00:05:27,458
10 years ago, he killed my
father and framed me for it.

98
00:05:27,541 --> 00:05:30,083
If I can expose him
and clear my name,

99
00:05:30,166 --> 00:05:31,666
I should get my position back,

100
00:05:31,750 --> 00:05:33,958
and all of the money
that's rightfully mine.

101
00:05:34,041 --> 00:05:35,791
I swear,

102
00:05:35,875 --> 00:05:37,666
no matter what,

103
00:05:37,750 --> 00:05:40,041
I'll be sure he pays
for what he's done.

104
00:05:40,125 --> 00:05:41,458
[sigh]

105
00:05:43,083 --> 00:05:44,041
[breeze humming]

106
00:05:44,125 --> 00:05:45,666
[water dripping]

107
00:05:49,958 --> 00:05:50,958
[running water]

108
00:05:53,083 --> 00:05:55,083
[VIDAUX] This should put us
on the other side of the wall.

109
00:05:56,041 --> 00:05:58,041
Now, let's look for a way
to the surface.

110
00:05:58,125 --> 00:05:59,750
-But how are we supposed to fi--
-[MAYUKA whines]

111
00:05:59,833 --> 00:06:00,708
[yelp]

112
00:06:00,791 --> 00:06:01,833
-Huh?
-Hmm?

113
00:06:01,916 --> 00:06:04,166
[gasping]

114
00:06:04,250 --> 00:06:05,416
Hey!

115
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:07,250
-[MAYUKA] What?
-Next to that pillar,

116
00:06:07,333 --> 00:06:08,541
I saw someone,

117
00:06:08,625 --> 00:06:09,625
-a shadow!
-[flashlight clicks]

118
00:06:09,708 --> 00:06:10,625
[MAYUKA]
Was it a ghost?!

119
00:06:11,958 --> 00:06:14,166
There! See it? Right there?

120
00:06:14,250 --> 00:06:15,750
[panting]

121
00:06:15,833 --> 00:06:16,833
♪

122
00:06:16,916 --> 00:06:18,291
[creaking]

123
00:06:18,375 --> 00:06:20,166
[MAYUKA and YURI screaming]

124
00:06:20,250 --> 00:06:22,083
Hmm...

125
00:06:22,166 --> 00:06:24,250
[VIDAUX] [sigh]
I thought so.

126
00:06:24,333 --> 00:06:26,125
This place is infested!

127
00:06:26,208 --> 00:06:28,083
Wait! Turn off the lights,

128
00:06:28,166 --> 00:06:30,291
-and cut the engine, too.
-What, why?

129
00:06:30,375 --> 00:06:32,333
[DERRIDA]
It's a low battery warning.

130
00:06:32,416 --> 00:06:35,375
The way their eyes are blinking
means they're in emergency mode.

131
00:06:35,458 --> 00:06:37,583
-[VIDAUX] Shut down the engine.
-[GRAHAM] Roger.

132
00:06:37,666 --> 00:06:39,041
[VIDAUX]
Explain, Derrida.

133
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:42,041
Sleep mode. They're out of fuel,
so they can't move.

134
00:06:42,125 --> 00:06:43,125
[BOTH whimpering]

135
00:06:43,208 --> 00:06:44,791
But they reacted to the light,

136
00:06:44,875 --> 00:06:46,625
so their sensors aren't dead.

137
00:06:46,708 --> 00:06:48,333
It's like they're on standby,

138
00:06:48,416 --> 00:06:50,166
preserving every bit
of battery they can

139
00:06:50,250 --> 00:06:52,500
in order to keep monitoring
their surroundings,

140
00:06:52,583 --> 00:06:55,333
and so they can counterattack
if there's hostile stimuli.

141
00:06:55,416 --> 00:06:56,875
If we don't trigger
those sensors,

142
00:06:56,958 --> 00:06:58,333
we should be able to pass.

143
00:06:59,291 --> 00:07:01,041
[VIDAUX]
You sure about this?

144
00:07:01,125 --> 00:07:04,125
If I was programming
them for militarization,

145
00:07:04,208 --> 00:07:05,750
that's what I would've done.

146
00:07:06,708 --> 00:07:07,791
[VIDAUX]
Okay, Graham.

147
00:07:07,875 --> 00:07:09,500
Shut down all sensors.

148
00:07:09,583 --> 00:07:11,208
Nice and quiet, now.

149
00:07:11,291 --> 00:07:12,875
[rubble crunching]

150
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,958
[DERRIDA]
Just how many are there?

151
00:07:19,666 --> 00:07:21,166
[BOTH whimpering]

152
00:07:26,041 --> 00:07:27,166
[crunch, smash]

153
00:07:27,250 --> 00:07:28,083
[gasp]

154
00:07:28,166 --> 00:07:30,166
[DZs humming, creaking]

155
00:07:35,666 --> 00:07:37,416
[whimpering, gasp]

156
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:39,166
[air rushing, thud]

157
00:07:39,250 --> 00:07:40,041
[BOTH gasp]

158
00:07:40,125 --> 00:07:41,083
♪

159
00:07:41,166 --> 00:07:42,791
[gasping]

160
00:07:42,875 --> 00:07:45,750
[humming continues]

161
00:07:45,833 --> 00:07:47,666
So, it comes down
to a fight anyway!

162
00:07:48,833 --> 00:07:50,041
[tires screeching]

163
00:07:50,125 --> 00:07:52,083
[smash]

164
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:56,875
[tires screeching]

165
00:07:56,958 --> 00:07:59,375
[groaning]

166
00:08:00,833 --> 00:08:02,375
[grunt]

167
00:08:03,541 --> 00:08:05,208
[humming]

168
00:08:05,291 --> 00:08:06,208
[blast]

169
00:08:07,625 --> 00:08:08,458
[thud]

170
00:08:08,541 --> 00:08:09,500
[tires screeching]

171
00:08:09,583 --> 00:08:10,916
[crash]

172
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:12,041
[electronics winding down]

173
00:08:12,125 --> 00:08:13,000
[beeping]

174
00:08:17,666 --> 00:08:19,416
[VIDAUX] Looks like you
were right, Derrida.

175
00:08:19,500 --> 00:08:22,500
They didn't pursue us
through the passageway.

176
00:08:22,583 --> 00:08:25,166
[YURI] But, there'll be
more at the next station.

177
00:08:25,250 --> 00:08:26,666
Don't worry.

178
00:08:26,750 --> 00:08:27,875
We should be able to take

179
00:08:27,958 --> 00:08:29,791
the construction workers'
stairway up.

180
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:31,166
[VIDAUX]
Hey, what about Graham?

181
00:08:31,250 --> 00:08:32,916
You suggesting
we leave him here?

182
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:35,166
[GRAHAM] I cannot endorse
this plan of action.

183
00:08:35,250 --> 00:08:37,083
No, not at all.

184
00:08:37,166 --> 00:08:38,708
We'll take Graham with us, too.

185
00:08:42,125 --> 00:08:43,041
[footsteps]

186
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:45,500
[DERRIDA]
Everything's ready.

187
00:08:45,583 --> 00:08:47,208
[VIDAUX]
I don't like this.

188
00:08:47,291 --> 00:08:49,875
♪

189
00:08:51,916 --> 00:08:53,166
[MAYUKA]
Hello! Hello!

190
00:08:53,250 --> 00:08:54,541
Testing, testing!

191
00:08:54,625 --> 00:08:55,708
[YURI]
Can you guys hear us?

192
00:08:55,791 --> 00:08:57,750
-Loud and clear, very good.
-Hmm?

193
00:08:57,833 --> 00:08:59,666
Now, Graham,
maximize the broadcast strength

194
00:08:59,750 --> 00:09:01,291
and encryption. You got it?

195
00:09:01,375 --> 00:09:02,750
[GRAHAM]
Roger that, sir.

196
00:09:02,833 --> 00:09:05,208
Huh! Was that actually
Graham's voice?

197
00:09:05,291 --> 00:09:07,208
-[GRAHAM] It's remote access.
-[VIDAUX] Hmm...

198
00:09:07,291 --> 00:09:09,125
I told you we'd be bringing him.

199
00:09:09,208 --> 00:09:10,541
Having a good A.I. on our side

200
00:09:10,625 --> 00:09:12,458
will make this
easier to pull off.

201
00:09:12,541 --> 00:09:14,000
-[growl]
-[GRAHAM] Much appreciated.

202
00:09:14,083 --> 00:09:17,416
Hey! Don't use Graham in
ways that I don't understand!

203
00:09:18,416 --> 00:09:20,750
Why not? It's a basic feature.

204
00:09:20,833 --> 00:09:22,000
Hey, Graham. Map, please.

205
00:09:22,083 --> 00:09:23,000
[beeping]

206
00:09:23,083 --> 00:09:24,291
[GRAHAM]
Acquiring data about

207
00:09:24,375 --> 00:09:26,250
Rebuild's staff
and security placement,

208
00:09:26,333 --> 00:09:28,791
using internal attendance
tracking system.

209
00:09:28,875 --> 00:09:31,333
Everyone's gone home.
Looking good.

210
00:09:31,416 --> 00:09:33,958
-Yeah, what makes you so sure?
-[chuckle]

211
00:09:34,041 --> 00:09:36,166
That's the benefit
of being former staff.

212
00:09:37,125 --> 00:09:38,750
If we use a fake pass
like this one,

213
00:09:38,833 --> 00:09:41,833
then even if the security robots
see us, they won't bother us.

214
00:09:41,916 --> 00:09:44,333
[VIDAUX] You seem awfully
familiar with all this.

215
00:09:44,416 --> 00:09:46,291
[DERRIDA] One of the first
things I did when I got hired

216
00:09:46,375 --> 00:09:48,125
was rig the time card system.

217
00:09:49,458 --> 00:09:52,083
I didn't want my work schedule
to be decided by some machines.

218
00:09:52,166 --> 00:09:54,541
Ah. I thought you were
a goodie-two-shoes type,

219
00:09:54,625 --> 00:09:56,583
but you had a real bad streak.

220
00:09:56,666 --> 00:09:58,541
-I'm impressed.
-Maybe.

221
00:09:58,625 --> 00:10:01,208
It just made me mad how they'd
force me out at quitting time,

222
00:10:01,291 --> 00:10:03,291
even if I wanted
to work all night.

223
00:10:03,375 --> 00:10:05,041
[VIDAUX]
Huh?

224
00:10:06,458 --> 00:10:08,291
[beeping]

225
00:10:08,375 --> 00:10:09,333
[doors slide open]

226
00:10:09,416 --> 00:10:10,625
[beeping]

227
00:10:16,625 --> 00:10:18,375
You don't have to
keep looking around.

228
00:10:18,458 --> 00:10:20,250
There's no one here.

229
00:10:20,333 --> 00:10:22,083
And this will fool the machines!

230
00:10:22,166 --> 00:10:25,041
Based on your memories
from 10 years ago, at least.

231
00:10:25,125 --> 00:10:27,916
Security is even lighter
than I remember, actually.

232
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:29,375
Even the guard's office
has been moved

233
00:10:29,458 --> 00:10:31,208
to the weapons
department floor.

234
00:10:32,250 --> 00:10:35,291
Guess this company really
is a defense contractor now.

235
00:10:37,750 --> 00:10:38,916
[DERRIDA]
Andrei...

236
00:10:40,041 --> 00:10:41,875
[elevator humming]

237
00:10:41,958 --> 00:10:42,833
[beep]

238
00:10:51,708 --> 00:10:53,250
So, this Andrei guy,

239
00:10:53,333 --> 00:10:56,166
what if he turned out to be
in the building right now?

240
00:10:56,250 --> 00:10:57,375
Huh?

241
00:10:57,458 --> 00:10:59,166
As if he would ever
stay this late.

242
00:10:59,250 --> 00:11:00,541
I'm talking hypothetically.

243
00:11:00,625 --> 00:11:02,625
If the man who killed
your best friend

244
00:11:02,708 --> 00:11:04,541
and your father
were here right now,

245
00:11:04,625 --> 00:11:06,291
what would you do?

246
00:11:07,541 --> 00:11:08,916
Well, I...

247
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:10,458
[VIDAUX]
I should make it clear,

248
00:11:10,541 --> 00:11:12,416
I won't take part in revenge.

249
00:11:12,500 --> 00:11:14,166
Not for any reason.

250
00:11:14,250 --> 00:11:16,416
If you're in this
to get vengeance,

251
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:18,166
I'm pulling out here and now.

252
00:11:18,250 --> 00:11:20,166
♪

253
00:11:20,250 --> 00:11:21,791
Another regulation of yours?

254
00:11:21,875 --> 00:11:24,041
No, more serious than that.

255
00:11:24,125 --> 00:11:27,125
It's a belief
I refuse to compromise.

256
00:11:27,208 --> 00:11:29,458
[DERRIDA] Even if the vengeance
would be righteous?

257
00:11:29,541 --> 00:11:30,875
Derrida.

258
00:11:30,958 --> 00:11:32,625
If you really believe
that there's such a thing

259
00:11:32,708 --> 00:11:34,666
as perfectly
righteous revenge,

260
00:11:34,750 --> 00:11:36,875
when the time comes,
find a mirror.

261
00:11:37,833 --> 00:11:39,333
[DERRIDA]
A mirror?

262
00:11:40,291 --> 00:11:42,458
[VIDAUX]
Look at your face, that's all.

263
00:11:44,208 --> 00:11:45,083
[beep]

264
00:11:54,416 --> 00:11:56,458
♪

265
00:11:59,333 --> 00:12:00,833
Okay, let's split up.

266
00:12:00,916 --> 00:12:03,291
I'll start by hitting
the executive suite.

267
00:12:03,375 --> 00:12:04,833
Yeah, okay.

268
00:12:04,916 --> 00:12:07,250
I'll check out my old lab,
it's just up ahead.

269
00:12:09,833 --> 00:12:11,625
[DERRIDA] We'll meet
at the elevator in 20.

270
00:12:11,708 --> 00:12:13,083
[VIDAUX]
Right.

271
00:12:15,041 --> 00:12:16,083
[door opens]

272
00:12:17,583 --> 00:12:18,625
[door closes]

273
00:12:24,500 --> 00:12:27,166
Nobody wanted
a murderer's old lab?

274
00:12:27,250 --> 00:12:29,208
I guess I understand that.

275
00:12:34,958 --> 00:12:35,875
[computer whirring]

276
00:12:35,958 --> 00:12:37,541
[typing]

277
00:12:38,708 --> 00:12:40,083
A password?

278
00:12:40,166 --> 00:12:42,166
That's pretty old-school.

279
00:12:42,250 --> 00:12:44,708
His last login was on...

280
00:12:44,791 --> 00:12:46,958
December 20th, 2050.

281
00:12:48,333 --> 00:12:49,458
That day.

282
00:12:50,416 --> 00:12:52,208
"Happy birthday."

283
00:12:52,291 --> 00:12:53,541
[clicking, creaking]

284
00:12:53,625 --> 00:12:55,208
[beeping]

285
00:13:00,666 --> 00:13:02,541
What kind of flower
did she like, again?

286
00:13:02,625 --> 00:13:03,416
♪

287
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:04,416
Mage...

288
00:13:06,666 --> 00:13:09,458
Take care... of Mage!

289
00:13:09,541 --> 00:13:10,875
[gasp]

290
00:13:10,958 --> 00:13:13,000
[groaning]

291
00:13:14,875 --> 00:13:15,916
[mechanical tick]

292
00:13:22,291 --> 00:13:23,583
[gasp]

293
00:13:24,750 --> 00:13:25,833
It's you again.

294
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:28,708
My name is Ange.

295
00:13:32,875 --> 00:13:35,166
[WOMAN, overlapping]
Clockwise. Anti-Clockwise.

296
00:13:39,541 --> 00:13:40,333
♪

297
00:13:40,416 --> 00:13:42,041
[DERRIDA]
Who are you?

298
00:13:42,125 --> 00:13:43,916
What's going on?

299
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:45,500
You're not Mage.

300
00:13:45,583 --> 00:13:47,458
[ANGE]
Mage is waiting for you.

301
00:13:48,916 --> 00:13:50,958
She's been waiting a long time.

302
00:13:54,541 --> 00:13:55,625
[heavy breathing]

303
00:13:55,708 --> 00:13:58,375
[DERRIDA]
I have to kill Andrei.

304
00:13:58,458 --> 00:14:00,416
I don't have time to hesitate.

305
00:14:00,500 --> 00:14:03,416
At this rate, Dad, Nathan,
and Mage will be...

306
00:14:04,666 --> 00:14:07,583
Do it! This is
the only right choice.

307
00:14:07,666 --> 00:14:08,541
[heavy breathing]

308
00:14:08,625 --> 00:14:10,541
[VIDAUX]
Look at your face.

309
00:14:10,625 --> 00:14:12,875
[heavy breathing]

310
00:14:16,125 --> 00:14:18,166
[wind swirling]

311
00:14:20,041 --> 00:14:21,708
[painful groaning]

312
00:14:24,416 --> 00:14:25,458
Ah!

313
00:14:27,875 --> 00:14:28,916
What the--

314
00:14:30,166 --> 00:14:31,750
What was I just doing?

315
00:14:33,333 --> 00:14:35,666
I was on my way to
the flower shop...

316
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:36,875
[gasp]

317
00:14:36,958 --> 00:14:38,541
[crackling, beeping]

318
00:14:40,041 --> 00:14:40,916
That was...

319
00:14:41,875 --> 00:14:43,125
-[door opens]
-[gasp]

320
00:14:43,208 --> 00:14:45,250
It's time, what're you doing?

321
00:14:46,375 --> 00:14:48,125
[gasp, grunt]

322
00:14:48,208 --> 00:14:50,208
I copied every file that
they had even vaguely

323
00:14:50,291 --> 00:14:51,375
relating to Madge Bilstein.

324
00:14:51,458 --> 00:14:52,833
What about you?

325
00:14:52,916 --> 00:14:54,208
Sorry, I'm on it now.

326
00:14:54,291 --> 00:14:55,416
Well, hurry up!

327
00:14:55,500 --> 00:14:56,916
I'll go stand watch.

328
00:14:57,916 --> 00:14:59,125
[growl]

329
00:14:59,208 --> 00:15:00,958
[click, typing]

330
00:15:01,041 --> 00:15:02,916
[DERRIDA]
This file...

331
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:06,333
Nathan had an information
source I didn't know about.

332
00:15:06,416 --> 00:15:08,000
Is that what
the password was for?

333
00:15:09,250 --> 00:15:11,125
This is...

334
00:15:11,208 --> 00:15:13,500
It... can't be!

335
00:15:13,583 --> 00:15:14,750
-[YURI] Someone's coming!
-Huh?

336
00:15:14,833 --> 00:15:17,166
Looks like a human
security force. Run!

337
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:19,166
Company!
We can't use the elevator.

338
00:15:19,250 --> 00:15:20,791
Let's take the security stairs!

339
00:15:21,750 --> 00:15:22,750
[panting]

340
00:15:25,500 --> 00:15:26,791
[DERRIDA]
The alarms aren't sounding!

341
00:15:26,875 --> 00:15:28,708
They don't know we're here yet!

342
00:15:29,666 --> 00:15:31,708
[panting]

343
00:15:34,750 --> 00:15:38,041
Just eight more floors and
we can get out into the park.

344
00:15:38,125 --> 00:15:40,416
We'll meet up with Graham
and make a plan.

345
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:42,000
Yuri, if you're not
sure about driving,

346
00:15:42,083 --> 00:15:43,541
now's the time to speak up.

347
00:15:43,625 --> 00:15:44,541
[YURI]
Leave it to me!

348
00:15:44,625 --> 00:15:46,250
That car's too conspicuous!

349
00:15:46,333 --> 00:15:48,875
We've managed to not make any
electronic footprints so far!

350
00:15:48,958 --> 00:15:50,041
If we just wait a while...

351
00:15:50,125 --> 00:15:51,416
All well and good,

352
00:15:51,500 --> 00:15:53,666
but somebody left
non-electronic footprints

353
00:15:53,750 --> 00:15:56,208
on that dusty lab
floor upstairs.

354
00:15:57,375 --> 00:15:58,666
[heavy breathing]

355
00:16:00,125 --> 00:16:01,208
[alarm blaring]

356
00:16:01,291 --> 00:16:03,041
-[bang]
-Damn it!

357
00:16:03,125 --> 00:16:05,041
I'll overlook a few
scratches on the car,

358
00:16:05,125 --> 00:16:06,166
so just gun it over here!

359
00:16:06,250 --> 00:16:07,125
♪

360
00:16:07,208 --> 00:16:08,416
-[roar]
-[MAYUKA] Got it!

361
00:16:08,500 --> 00:16:09,750
Okay, let's hit it!

362
00:16:09,833 --> 00:16:12,375
So, this is what
a steering wheel feels like.

363
00:16:12,458 --> 00:16:13,458
Huh?

364
00:16:13,541 --> 00:16:14,875
How's it start?

365
00:16:15,958 --> 00:16:18,000
[tires screeching]

366
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:24,208
[metal scraping]

367
00:16:25,416 --> 00:16:27,083
[swoop, thud]

368
00:16:27,166 --> 00:16:29,208
[tires screeching]

369
00:16:31,750 --> 00:16:34,125
You told Papa that you
were sure you could drive!

370
00:16:34,208 --> 00:16:35,666
Mmm!

371
00:16:35,750 --> 00:16:38,375
[YURI] I'm definitely getting
my license this year!

372
00:16:47,166 --> 00:16:49,333
He told us to gun it, remember?

373
00:16:53,750 --> 00:16:55,250
I'm coming, Derrida.

374
00:16:55,333 --> 00:16:56,666
Hang in there.

375
00:16:57,625 --> 00:16:59,125
You really like him, huh?

376
00:16:59,208 --> 00:17:01,416
You guys would be cute together!

377
00:17:01,500 --> 00:17:03,541
Huh, what's that?
Can't hear you!

378
00:17:03,625 --> 00:17:05,500
[doors slamming]

379
00:17:08,208 --> 00:17:10,083
[DERRIDA panting]

380
00:17:11,666 --> 00:17:12,875
[gunshots]

381
00:17:13,958 --> 00:17:15,125
[grunt]

382
00:17:15,208 --> 00:17:17,291
♪

383
00:17:17,375 --> 00:17:18,458
[gunfire]

384
00:17:18,541 --> 00:17:19,541
[explosion]

385
00:17:19,625 --> 00:17:21,500
[panting]

386
00:17:21,583 --> 00:17:22,416
Almost!

387
00:17:23,833 --> 00:17:25,958
[tires screeching]

388
00:17:27,791 --> 00:17:29,166
Get ready to jump, Derrida!

389
00:17:29,250 --> 00:17:30,125
Huh?

390
00:17:32,041 --> 00:17:32,833
[grunt]

391
00:17:32,916 --> 00:17:34,500
[air rushing]

392
00:17:35,916 --> 00:17:37,500
-[tires screeching]
-[banging]

393
00:17:38,958 --> 00:17:40,500
[thuds, grunts]

394
00:17:42,375 --> 00:17:43,666
[smash]

395
00:17:43,750 --> 00:17:45,375
[buzzing, humming]

396
00:17:46,333 --> 00:17:47,416
Yahoo!

397
00:17:48,833 --> 00:17:50,166
-[camera snap]
-[giggle]

398
00:17:50,250 --> 00:17:52,208
-Take your wall and shove it!
-[camera snap]

399
00:17:53,708 --> 00:17:54,708
[camera snap]

400
00:17:54,791 --> 00:17:55,833
[gasp]

401
00:17:56,791 --> 00:17:58,291
Derrida?

402
00:18:01,541 --> 00:18:03,333
[VIDAUX]
That was rough.

403
00:18:03,416 --> 00:18:04,916
What a crazy ride.

404
00:18:05,000 --> 00:18:07,333
[snoring]

405
00:18:07,416 --> 00:18:09,958
Any luck finding out
where Mage might be?

406
00:18:10,041 --> 00:18:11,333
[VIDAUX]
Not yet.

407
00:18:11,416 --> 00:18:13,083
But hopefully we'll be able
to find something

408
00:18:13,166 --> 00:18:15,500
in this mountain of files
we took from Rebuild.

409
00:18:15,583 --> 00:18:17,666
That's great, it means
there's a chance!

410
00:18:17,750 --> 00:18:19,458
Isn't that right, Derrida?

411
00:18:20,500 --> 00:18:22,416
Uh. Hey, what's wrong?

412
00:18:22,500 --> 00:18:24,166
Well, it...

413
00:18:24,250 --> 00:18:26,000
It's good news about Mage, yeah.

414
00:18:27,000 --> 00:18:28,416
But...

415
00:18:32,333 --> 00:18:34,833
[typing]

416
00:18:35,791 --> 00:18:36,916
-[YURI] Hmm?
-[VIDAUX] Hmm.

417
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:38,375
[gasp]

418
00:18:38,458 --> 00:18:40,375
[DERRIDA]
I thought that it was Andrei,

419
00:18:40,458 --> 00:18:42,500
who was behind
the incident 10 years ago.

420
00:18:43,458 --> 00:18:45,250
That he was trying
to kill off people

421
00:18:45,333 --> 00:18:48,666
who knew about the DZ bug,
to keep the secret hidden.

422
00:18:48,750 --> 00:18:49,875
[YURI]
But, it wasn't?

423
00:18:49,958 --> 00:18:51,875
[DERRIDA]
That data shows

424
00:18:51,958 --> 00:18:53,750
that the DZ bug
was manufactured

425
00:18:53,833 --> 00:18:55,041
and put in there
intentionally.

426
00:18:55,125 --> 00:18:57,208
-But, why?
-How do you know this?

427
00:18:57,291 --> 00:18:59,875
[DERRIDA] It's signed by all
the executives except my father.

428
00:18:59,958 --> 00:19:01,666
Government officials, too.

429
00:19:01,750 --> 00:19:03,708
That can only mean...

430
00:19:03,791 --> 00:19:05,458
the DZ rampage was engineered

431
00:19:05,541 --> 00:19:08,250
by the government
and Rebuild from the start.

432
00:19:08,333 --> 00:19:10,083
I don't understand.

433
00:19:10,166 --> 00:19:11,541
When the DZs went haywire,

434
00:19:11,625 --> 00:19:13,958
it turned the war
completely upside down.

435
00:19:14,041 --> 00:19:15,500
He thinks it was
done on purpose,

436
00:19:15,583 --> 00:19:17,958
by people who stood to
benefit from the chaos.

437
00:19:18,041 --> 00:19:18,875
No way.

438
00:19:18,958 --> 00:19:19,958
♪

439
00:19:20,041 --> 00:19:20,958
[DERRIDA]
The patch file I made,

440
00:19:21,041 --> 00:19:23,250
they don't need it at all.

441
00:19:23,333 --> 00:19:25,125
They'd actually prefer
to be rid of it!

442
00:19:26,958 --> 00:19:28,166
[DERRIDA]
It isn't just Rebuild

443
00:19:28,250 --> 00:19:30,416
who's after the access key
for the patch.

444
00:19:30,500 --> 00:19:31,875
It's the government,

445
00:19:31,958 --> 00:19:34,125
and the other countries
involved in the war, too.

446
00:19:34,208 --> 00:19:35,083
[sigh]

447
00:19:36,458 --> 00:19:38,125
Vidaux.
It's time we parted ways.

448
00:19:38,208 --> 00:19:40,708
I won't drag you
any deeper into this.

449
00:19:40,791 --> 00:19:43,083
I'll pay you the money
I owe you, I promise.

450
00:19:43,166 --> 00:19:45,416
Could you just take Yuri
somewhere safe for me?

451
00:19:45,500 --> 00:19:47,166
Derrida!

452
00:19:47,250 --> 00:19:48,791
[DERRIDA] It was my misplaced
optimism that caused this mess!

453
00:19:48,875 --> 00:19:50,166
Wait, hold on!

454
00:19:50,250 --> 00:19:52,416
It isn't only your fault.

455
00:19:52,500 --> 00:19:54,083
I also...

456
00:19:54,166 --> 00:19:55,916
Yuri?

457
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:57,833
So, what's your plan?

458
00:19:57,916 --> 00:20:00,916
I need to find Mage first,
no matter what.

459
00:20:01,000 --> 00:20:02,291
Then, I wanna do
something about

460
00:20:02,375 --> 00:20:04,000
this endless gridlock of a war!

461
00:20:04,916 --> 00:20:06,583
Hmm...

462
00:20:06,666 --> 00:20:09,666
When a man discovers something
more valuable than his revenge,

463
00:20:10,916 --> 00:20:12,208
he's earned my assistance.

464
00:20:12,291 --> 00:20:13,166
[gasp]

465
00:20:16,791 --> 00:20:18,000
[sigh]

466
00:20:18,083 --> 00:20:19,791
Oh, is that so?

467
00:20:19,875 --> 00:20:21,000
Another of your regulations?

468
00:20:21,083 --> 00:20:22,916
No sir.

469
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:25,041
Spur of the moment choice.

470
00:20:25,125 --> 00:20:27,750
I actually got a copy
of your data, too.

471
00:20:27,833 --> 00:20:30,416
You have quite a fortune,
based on patents alone.

472
00:20:32,541 --> 00:20:34,541
Once we've got
your name cleared,

473
00:20:34,625 --> 00:20:36,500
I'll accept all
of it as payment.

474
00:20:37,458 --> 00:20:39,500
♪

475
00:20:47,875 --> 00:20:49,291
[MAN 1]
So then,

476
00:20:49,375 --> 00:20:51,958
do we have a final report
on the rampaging Automata?

477
00:20:52,916 --> 00:20:54,500
Anyone?

478
00:20:54,583 --> 00:20:56,791
[MAN 2] We've concluded
it is no longer possible

479
00:20:56,875 --> 00:20:59,625
to settle the situation
through normal methods.

480
00:21:00,791 --> 00:21:02,250
[MAN 3]
Pandora's box is open,

481
00:21:02,333 --> 00:21:04,166
and there's no way
to close it, then.

482
00:21:04,250 --> 00:21:05,958
That's what you're saying?

483
00:21:11,583 --> 00:21:12,875
[typing]

484
00:21:12,958 --> 00:21:15,041
♪

485
00:21:15,125 --> 00:21:16,250
Huh?

486
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:18,125
[footsteps]

487
00:21:18,208 --> 00:21:20,250
-You thinking?
-Yeah.

488
00:21:20,333 --> 00:21:22,750
I had a dream about
Mage's birthday.

489
00:21:23,708 --> 00:21:25,500
Thing is, in the dream,
I was...

490
00:21:26,458 --> 00:21:29,041
[chuckle] Well, it would've made
me late, so it's impossible.

491
00:21:29,125 --> 00:21:31,791
You mean her birthday
party 10 years ago?

492
00:21:31,875 --> 00:21:33,541
But, you were late that day.

493
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:35,791
Huh?

494
00:21:35,875 --> 00:21:38,125
I mean, you got there
after I did, at least.

495
00:21:38,208 --> 00:21:39,125
[click]

496
00:21:39,208 --> 00:21:40,416
Hmm...

497
00:21:40,500 --> 00:21:42,375
[MAGE]
Coming!

498
00:21:42,458 --> 00:21:43,291
[doors creak]

499
00:21:43,375 --> 00:21:45,166
You're late, Derrida!

500
00:21:45,250 --> 00:21:46,291
-[splat]
-[gasp]

501
00:21:46,375 --> 00:21:47,875
[YURI laughing]

502
00:21:47,958 --> 00:21:49,916
[DERRIDA]
Uh, happy birthday, Mage!

503
00:21:51,875 --> 00:21:53,291
[DERRIDA]
Did I...

504
00:21:53,375 --> 00:21:55,166
change things...

505
00:21:55,250 --> 00:21:56,541
with a time ride?

506
00:21:57,625 --> 00:21:59,666
Did I experience
a different past?

507
00:21:59,750 --> 00:22:01,416
♪

508
00:22:01,500 --> 00:22:03,333
[DERRIDA]
Uh, happy birthday, Mage!

509
00:22:03,416 --> 00:22:04,958
[laughing]

510
00:22:05,041 --> 00:22:06,833
It's not that funny,
stop laughing!

511
00:22:07,791 --> 00:22:08,833
[gasp]

